                                <h2>The World</h2>
                                <p>Stromgard is a fictional realm within Midgard, the plane of mortals.  The people of Stromgard are hardy but poor and they value strength, self sufficiency, and honor.  They are a fairly lawful sort, as much as can be expected in a collection of rural settlements, but reputation and morality are weighed heavily in the communities, especially in human ones. 
                                <h3>Societies</h3>
                                <p>Stromgard is primarily populated by humans, who live in a multitude of settlements strewn about the land.  Elves and dwarves both live in Stromgard in great numbers, the former gravitating towards their forest cities and the latter burrowing into every mountain in the region.  Gnomes are also commonly found, typically living close to dwarven communities.  Halfings are also a staple of Stromgardian populations, though they typically only settle where the land is fertile and easily farmed.  More often than not, these societies tend to be racially insular to some degree, though there is no standing bad blood or open feuds between any of these groups as a whole.  Above looks and race, in Stromgard, your honor and strength say more about your worth across all communities.</p>
                                <h3>Conquest</h3>
                                <p>More than anything else, life in Stromgard (for humans, at any rate) is fueled by conquest and exploration.  Every spring, the realm prepares to send out its best boats, helmsmen, and warriors to find new land and also sack the hell out of it.  It is a brutal practice, but the rewards and glory are plentiful.  As is the iminent danger of sea monsters, other warriors, and storms.  Warriors that bring new resources or settle far off lands or even make treaties with foreign ports are lavishly decorated on their return, and their war spoils open many doors for them.</p>
                                <h3>The Nine Realms</h3>
                                <p>The Gods say that the world as we know it sits spread out on the branches of a cosmic tree, divided into nine seperate realms, or planes, as follows:</p>
                                <div class="realms">
                                <p><strong>Asgard</strong> - Home to the Aesir gods and Odin, chief among them</p>
                                <p>
                                    <strong>Vanaheim</strong> - Realm of the lesser gods, the Vanir
</p>
                                <p>
                                    <strong>Alfheim</strong> - Realm of the divine light elves
</p>
                                <p>
                                    <strong>Myrkheim</strong> - Ancestral home of the dwarven peoples
</p>
                                <p>
                                    <strong>Midgard</strong> - Realm of mortals, surrounded by J&oumltunheim, the icy land of the J&oumltnar
</p>
                                <p>
                                    <strong>Svaralfheim</strong> - Home of the rarely seen and extremely insular divine moon elves
</p>
                                <p>
                                    <strong>Hel</strong> - this realm, ruled by the goddess Hel, houses the dead
</p>
                                <p>
                                    <strong>Niflheim</strong> - A special subrealm of Hel for the dishonorable dead
</p>
                                <p>
                                    <strong>Muspelheim</strong> - A plane of pure fire and ash that houses the fire giants and their god-king, Surt
</p>
                                </div>
                                 
                                <h3>The Gods</h3>
                                <p>There are countless deities worshipped all over in varying capacities, their are, however, a few exalted powers that are ubiquitous throughout Stromgard.  Technically, even some ancient and immense J&oumltnar are considered to be gods in their own right.</p>
                                <div class="realms">
                                    <p>
                                        <strong>Odin</strong> - Chief among the Aesir deities.  Associated with wisdom, honorable warfare, and prophecy.  It is said that he wanders the world disguised as an old man.
</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <strong>Thor</strong> - A noble and mighty warrior that champions honorable combat, battle prowess, and storms.  Sometimes, Thor is also associated with masculinity and virility, depending on the region.
</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <strong>Tyr</strong> - The voice of law, logic, and reason in Asgard.  Tyr is associated with honorable glory and due process.
</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <strong>Loki</strong> - An enigma.  Loki is considered an Aesir deity but his mixed J&oumltnar parentage make his motives difficult to understand.  Above all, Loki prizes cleverness and wits in his devotees and usually seeks to subvert convention as much as possible.  He is especially honored amongst the outcasted.
</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <strong>Freya</strong> - The warrior goddess Freya is sometimes considered an Aesir and sometimes a Vanir, depending on the region.  She is a formidable fighter and the idol of female warriors of all races.  Freya especially looks kindly on spellweavers and helps the Valkyries sort the honorable dead.
</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <strong>Freyr</strong> - A Vanir god of light and the god to whom the Alfir are most devoted to.  He is associated with sacral authority, the sun, the cycle of seasons, and prospertity.
</p>
                                </div> 
